05632nam a22008295i 9780812208313DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132013pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)922641260  a(OCoLC)999354588  a97808122083137 a10.9783/97808122083132doi  a(DE-B1597)449696  a(OCoLC)859161692  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0380002bisacsh04a331.11/7340972981090322231 aNewman, Simon P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA New World of Labor :bThe Development of Plantation Slavery in the British Atlantic /cSimon P. Newman. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b15 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Early Modern Americas00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPART I. Settings -- tChapter 1. England -- tChapter 2. The Gold Coast -- tChapter 3. Barbados -- tPART II. British Bound Labor -- tChapter 4. ‘‘White Slaves’’ -- tChapter 5. ‘‘A Company of White Negroes’’ -- tPART III. African Bound Labor -- tChapter 6. ‘‘A Spirit of Liberty’’ -- tChapter 7. ‘‘We Have No Power over Them’’ -- tPART IV. Plantation Slavery -- tChapter 8. ‘‘The Harsh Tyranny of Our Masters’’ -- tChapter 9. ‘‘Forced to Labour Beyond Their Natural Strength’’ -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe small and remote island of Barbados seems an unlikely location for the epochal change in labor that overwhelmed it and much of British America in the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries. However, by 1650 it had become the greatest wealth-producing area in the English-speaking world, the center of an exchange of people and goods between the British Isles, the Gold Coast of West Africa, and the New World. By the early seventeenth century, more than half a million enslaved men, women, and children had been transported to the island. In A New World of Labor, Simon P. Newman argues that this exchange stimulated an entirely new system of bound labor.Free and bound labor were defined and experienced by Britons and Africans across the British Atlantic world in quite different ways. Connecting social developments in seventeenth-century Britain with the British experience of slavery on the West African coast, Newman demonstrates that the brutal white servant regime, rather than the West African institution of slavery, provided the most significant foundation for the violent system of racialized black slavery that developed in Barbados. Class as much as race informed the creation of plantation slavery in Barbados and throughout British America. Enslaved Africans in Barbados were deployed in radically new ways in order to cultivate, process, and manufacture sugar on single, integrated plantations. This Barbadian system informed the development of racial slavery on Jamaica and other Caribbean islands, as well as in South Carolina and then the Deep South of mainland British North America. Drawing on British and West African precedents, and then radically reshaping them, Barbados planters invented a new world of labor.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBritishzGhanaxHistory. 0aContract laborzBarbadosxHistory. 0aPlantationszBarbadosxHistory. 0aSlave laborzBarbadosxHistory. 0aSlave laborzGhanaxHistory. 4aLatin American. 7aHISTORY / Americas (North, Central, South, West Indies).2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aCaribbean Studies.  aLatin American Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package American Historyz978311041349608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook P